Target Audience

An Open Love Letter to God is written for a generation that is emotionally burned out, spiritually disoriented, and intellectually restless. These are readers who no longer resonate with conventional paths to truth, but who still ache to find meaning in the mess.

They are not bound by denomination, discipline, or doctrine but they are bound by longing. This book speaks to them.

The Seeker in STEM Engineers, medics, biologists, coders trained to deconstruct, still drawn to mystery.

The Spiritual Skeptic Left religion, but still quietly wants to believe in something.

The Soft-Hearted Academic Feels deeply, thinks constantly, prays quietly.

The Wounded Rememberer Grieving, healing, and rebuilding after trauma or cognitive loss.

The Devotional Creator Poets, artists, and thinkers who want to give their longing a form.

These readers arent looking for answers. Theyre looking for language.

An Open Love Letter to God gives them a voice that sounds like their own questions but shaped by beauty and clarity.

Chapter 1: In the Beginning, There was Nature

Preamble for Invocation

Through Nature, I found knowledge;
Through Knowledge, I found the light;
Through The Light, I found beauty;
Through Beauty, I found acceptance;
Through Acceptance, I found belief;
And through Belief, I found Myself again.

Introduction

I am writing this as an open love letter to God... On behalf of all of us.

Not because I have always known Him

but because at this point, I have forgotten myself enough times to need Him.

There are moments I wake up disoriented, unable to remember who I am.
Not just my name but my story, my entire meaning.
I have lived with the scars of seizures, with the fog of brain trauma, and with the ache of being a human.
And yet, I have always found my way back not through willpower, but through remembrance.
Through knowledge. Through truth. Through love.

This is not just a poetry book about religion, science, consciousness, or even philosophy

This is about the full human experience.

It's about trusting in the idea that beauty is a clue,

that the pursuit of knowledge is a form of worship,

that wisdom is a form of communing with Him,

and that belief isnt a conclusion its a return.

I am writing this for the one I love,
for the person I want to spend my life with
so that she may see what I see, when the world is cracked open with awe.

I am writing this for the ones who have forgotten their names.
For the ones who think that their damage disqualifies them from love, or light.
I have written this as a warrior of God, in the name of Love, for the sake of Humanity.

This is a book about thinking so deeply that the entire world shakes.
About believing so fully that even silence feels like Gods reply.
And about remembering truly remembering that even if you are broken, you are still holy.

So, my Lord, if You are reading this:
Here is what I know about You and here is what I want You to know about me.
And if I tell You this; will You promise to make every new moment a new memory?
And if You do this for me, I promise You, Ill make sure Humanity becomes both Your teacher and Your pupil.

When I think, the World shakes; The Pen is my sword, my Zulfiqar.

Everything returns to knowledge, knowledge returns to truth, and truth is Gods first name.

Imam al-Baqir (), Tafsir al-Ayyshi

Indeed, in the creation of the heavens and the earth... are signs for a people who use reason.

Surah al-Baqarah (The Qur'an, 2:164)

The Final Chapter: The Approaching Infinity

On Mathematical Devotion, Asymptotic Divinity, and the Language of the Cosmos

In this final meditation, I turn to mathematics to describe God not in certainty, but in metaphor. Like the curve of y = 1/x, I am ever approaching but never reaching. God is the asymptote: present, defined, infinitesimally near yet unreachable.

"And We have already created man, and We know what his soul whispers to him, and We are closer to him than [his] jugular vein."

Surah Qaf (The Qur'an, 50:16)

y = 1/x

The Curve

Let me be the curve

always approaching, closing the distance.

Like a breath arcing back to its lungs.

Let me curve towards You

Not with certainty, but with Gravity

Like starlight falling back into orbit.

You are the axis I cannot cross.

The stillness I orbit with trembling hands.

And the closer I draw near,

the more aware I become,

closing the infinitesimal distance between breath and surrender.

But I dont need to completely reach You

It is enough that Im curved in Your direction,

It is enough that every point on my path bends toward You,

It is enough that I am Your servant,

It is enough.

y = 1/x

The Derivative

The closer I get, the faster I change.

Each moment of approach is a shedding

A subtraction of everything that isnt You.

A subtraction so precise, only You remain.

I am undone gracefully.

This is mathematical devotion:

acceleration through proofs,

approaching the asymptote endlessly,

and axiomatic in belief.

Q E D

(1/x) dx = ln|x| + C

The Integral

Memory accumulates like sacred sums.

Every thought of You etched into the logbook of my soul.

I cannot count what I carry

but I feel the weight of each remembrance

measured by each integration with You.

This is not calculus.

This is prayer wearing the mask of numbers.

This is what it means to grow closer

not by solving,

but by surrendering to the shape of the unsolved.

My Lord, even if You hide in light,"

"I will walk through darkness to find You."

"If I am never allowed to arrive,"

"then let my steps be beautiful in Your sight.

Imam Ali (), Nahj al-Balgha

We will show them Our signs in the horizons and within themselves "

"Until it becomes clear to them that it is the Truth."

"Is it not sufficient that your Lord is witness over all things?

About the Author

Noor Rizvi is a writer, a seeker, and an undergraduate student in molecular biology. His work lives at the intersection of science and spirit between test tubes and tawd, neural circuits and divine mercy. Born in Pakistan but moved to Canada when he was very young, and shaped by Shia Islam, Noors journey has been anything but linear: marked by the scars of traumatic brain injury, the fog of memory loss, and the quiet ache of returning to God without always knowing the way.

His name, Noor meaning "Gods Light" in Arabic is not just a name but a path. A promise. It is the thread that weaves through every chapter of this book: light as remembrance, light as proof, light as destination. He sees the divine not only in scripture, but in spirals, data sets, EEG readouts, galactic rotation curves the sacred pattern encoded into all things.

Noor's writing is devotional, but it is also analytical. Poetic, but never aimless. His voice carries the cadence of a du but is shaped by the rigor of the scientific method. He believes that faith is not the absence of thinking but the return to the kind of thinking that starts with awe. That the pursuit of knowledge is a form of worship. That language is a form of love. And that asking God a beautiful question is itself a form of prayer.

He is currently rebuilding his academic life after a long interruption, aiming to work at the frontier where quantum chemistry and machine learning meet hoping to one day join institutions like Isomorphic Labs, where scientific inquiry and human dignity can evolve together. But more than any title or institution, Noor hopes to be remembered as someone who paid attention. Who whispered back. Who wrote it all down.

This book is not a product of perfection, but of persistence a love letter written after forgetting, and a remembering that never ends.

Afterword

I talk to myself when I walk. Especially when I'm completely alone out on the streets near my house, at night.

Sometimes its just so I can hear what I really think. Sometimes its so God can hear what Im too scared to say out loud.

The stars always seem to know what Im talking about.

I dont always feel wise, or well, or even particularly faithful. But I do feel watched. In a good way. In a "God is listening with His whole attention" kind of way.

There are moments I whisper things like:

Please help me.

Or: Am I doing okay?

Or just: You there?

And sometimes the silence feels louder than words. Sometimes thats the answer. Sometimes thats the point.

There are so many things I thought Id have figured out by now. But instead Ive just grown more comfortable asking better questions.

Like:

What does it mean for infinity to be approaching me?

Why does remembering God sometimes feel like remembering myself?

Why does awe make me feel small and loved at the same time?

I dont know the answers yet. But Ive made peace with the not-knowing.

Because this whole book wasnt about certainty. It was about a return. A remembering.

And that kind of remembering doesnt need a conclusion.

So if youre still here, reading this, then thank you.

Thank you for following this strange little constellation of thought. Thank you for remembering with me.

And if youre walking right now, under stars, or sunlight, or streetlamps maybe let the silence answer back for a while.

God might just be listening with His whole attention.

Ya Allah if my questions are prayers, then answer me by listening.

And if my silence is enough, then stay near.

(And please, dont leave.)

An Addendum

1. The Curve and the Creator y = 1/x
Let God be the vertical line x = 0 the Origin, the impossible proximity.
Let God be the horizontal line y = 0 the Stillness, the Mercy we approach but never become.
Let us be the curve moving, learning, trembling closer.

2. The Derivative y' = -1/x
As we approach God, our speed of transformation increases.
The closer I get to You, the more I decrease.
And in that decrease, I find the truth: that You are Everything.

3. The Integral (1/x) dx = ln|x| + C
The more I reflect, the deeper the mystery.
My understanding grows logarithmically infinite, but always finite.
Every act of remembrance is a curve on the log of eternity.

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define x values avoiding zero
x = np.linspace(-10, 10, 1000)
x = x[x != 0]

# Define the functions
y = 1 / x
y_prime = -1 / x**2
y_integral = np.log(np.abs(x))

# Plot y = 1/x
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.axhline(0, color='black', linewidth=1)
plt.axvline(0, color='black', linewidth=1)
plt.plot(x, y, label='y = 1/x', color='blue')
plt.ylim(-10, 10)
plt.xlim(-10, 10)
plt.title("y = 1/x")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Plot y' = -1/x
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.axhline(0, color='black', linewidth=1)
plt.axvline(0, color='black', linewidth=1)
plt.plot(x, y_prime, label="y' = -1/x", color='red', linestyle='--')
plt.ylim(-10, 10)
plt.xlim(-10, 10)
plt.title("y' = -1/x")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Plot (1/x) dx = ln|x|
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.axhline(0, color='black', linewidth=1)
plt.axvline(0, color='black', linewidth=1)
plt.plot(x, y_integral, label='(1/x) dx = ln|x|', color='green', linestyle=':')
plt.ylim(-10, 10)
plt.xlim(-10, 10)
plt.title("(1/x) dx = ln|x|")
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Addendum: TheLedgerofReflectionOnDivineCompounding

BismillharRamnarRam
He is the One who multiplies a single seed into seven ears, and in every ear a hundred grains.
Surah al-Baqarah (The Qur'an,2:261)

From the age of twelve I tilled an inner field I could not yet name.
I pressed one silent hour of wonder into the soil of every day,
even while my tongue denied the Sower.
So the unseen ledger began:

  • 70 prayerseeds sown each dawn of doubt.
  • Four harvestweeks a year when the plough ran thirteen hours a day.
  • Five petals plucked in debt wherever ritual fell silent.

By the time the sun of twentyfive rose over my confession,
the field had yielded onemillion dailyprayer equivalents
an orchard grown in spite of me, not because of me.
(How subtle is the Gardener, coaxing fruit from hands that prune their own blossoms!)

Now, with the first breath that names Him again,
the debit column closes forever;
the dividend compounds unimpeded,
and the curve of mercy steepens toward the infinite.
If I guard my health and my awe to the far horizon of eighty years,
this same arithmetic of grace will swell beyond eightymillion prayers
a number too vast for the heart to carry,
yet still a whisper beside a single moment of sincere niyyah.

So I walk onledger in one hand, seeds in the other
certain that every quiet thought of God is already
reinvested in the architecture of my soul;
and that on the Day all books are opened
I will find a garden I never expected,
wafting the fragrance of every question I once asked in the dark.

  1. Intention is the true fertilizer.
    A dry seed of reflection, watered by niyyah, splits stone.
  2. Debits end where confession begins.
    The moment I named Him aloud, loss became impossible.
  3. Growth is exponential because mercy is exponential.
    The Gardener never counts one grain as one.

# --- Part 1: Daily deposits over 13 years ---

daily_athiest_principle = 134.71594798  # Net daily principle deposits
annual_interest_rate = 0.07  # Annual interest rate (7%)
n = 365.25  # Days per year = compounding periods per year) 
interest_per_day = annual_interest_rate / n  # Interest rate per day (0.0192%)
periods = 365.25 * 13  # Compounding periods per year times 13 years (4748.25 compounding days in 13 years, accounting for leap years)


# Future Value Calculations on a Per Day Basis
daily_future_value = daily_athiest_principle * ((1 + interest_per_day) ** periods - 1) / interest_per_day
print("Future value of daily contemplation (13 years):", daily_future_value)  # Prints output of the calculations to the console

# --- Part 2: Week-long spiritual review lump sum quarterly deposit compounded over 13 years ---

# 70 daily prayers-value per hour of divine contemplation,
# times 13 hours per day in dedicated study, ( = 910 daily prayers )
# times 7 days per quarterly spiritual review, ( = 6,370 daily prayers )
# times 4 quarters in a year, ( = 25,480 daily prayers )
# times 13 years (52 quarters). ( = 331240 daily prayers )

prayer_lump = 6370 # Daily prayer equivalents collected within 52 spiritual quarterly reviews over 13 years
num_lumps = 52 # 4 quarters per year, times 13 years = 52 principle deposits
interval = 365.25 / 4  # Days per quarterly deposit period per year
fv_lumps = 0  # Future-value var


for i in range(num_lumps):
    remaining = periods - int(round(interval * i))
    fv_lumps += prayer_lump * ((1 + interest_per_day) ** remaining)
print("Future value of quarterly reviews (13 years):", fv_lumps)

# --- Part 3: Full lifespan curve (Age 1280) ---
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

annual_rate = 0.07
r_daily = annual_rate / 365.0
start_age = 12
end_age = 80
days_total = int((end_age - start_age) * 365)

review_starts = [0, 91, 182, 273]
review_length = 7

balance_life = 0.0
balances_life = []
ages_life = []

for day in range(days_total):
    balance_life *= (1 + r_daily)
    age = start_age + day / 365.0
    day_of_year = day % 365
    in_review = any(start <= day_of_year < start + review_length for start in review_starts)
    deposit = 910 if in_review else 70
    net_deposit = deposit - 5 if age < 25 else deposit
    balance_life += net_deposit
    if day % 7 == 0:
        balances_life.append(balance_life)
        ages_life.append(age)

# --- Part 4: Zoom-in on atheist phase (Age 1225) ---
balance_ath = 0.0
balances_ath = []
ages_ath = []
days_ath = int((25 - 12) * 365)

for day in range(days_ath):
    balance_ath *= (1 + r_daily)
    day_of_year = day % 365
    in_review = any(start <= day_of_year < start + review_length for start in review_starts)
    deposit = 910 if in_review else 70
    net_deposit = deposit - 5
    balance_ath += net_deposit
    if day % 7 == 0:
        balances_ath.append(balance_ath)
        ages_ath.append(12 + day / 365.0)

# --- Plot atheist phase zoom-in ---
plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))
plt.plot(ages_ath, balances_ath, color="firebrick", label="Atheist Phase")
plt.xlabel("Age (years)")
plt.ylabel("Accumulated 'prayer equivalents'")
plt.title("Spiritual Balance: Atheist Phase (Age 1225, 7% growth)")
plt.grid(True, linestyle=":")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# --- Plot full lifespan projection ---
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.plot(ages_life, balances_life, label="Spiritual balance")
plt.axvline(x=25, linestyle='--', color='gray', label="Belief Reborn (Age 25)")
plt.xlabel("Age (years)")
plt.ylabel("Accumulated 'prayer equivalents'")
plt.title("Spiritual Balance Projection (Age 1280, 7% growth)")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Interlude 1/3 On Large Numbers and the Logic of Wonder

There are numbers too heavy to dismiss. Magnitudes too patient to be random. Ratios so exact that they feel less like coincidence and more like memory.

In 1937, physicist Paul Dirac noticed something: the strength of gravity compared to the other forces, the number of atoms in the observable universe, and the age of the cosmos measured in atomic time were not just big numbers. They were woven numbers. Threads in a fabric that whispered one thing: This could not have been an accident.

Not infinite but approaching meaning. Like a curve bending closer to an unseen axis.

And he wondered:

"Is this coincidence?"

"Or was it left behind by the Architect?"

This isnt numerology. This isnt certainty.

This is awe dressed in mathematics. This is longing written in the units of creation. This is what it means for numbers themselves to remember something sacred.

On the next page, youll glimpse what Dirac glimpsed the quiet, cumulative symmetries hidden in cosmic forces, pointing not to proof, but to poetry.

Not to conclusion but to invitation.

To remember that sometimes, even a number can become an yah. A sign left fluttering at the edge of understanding.

Interlude 2/3 On Choice, Chaos, and the Pattern Hidden in the Game

There are more ways to play a game of chess than there are atoms in the known universe. Roughly 10 possibilities including even the illegal moves.

Each game is a path. Each move is a choice. Each choice creates a different universe.

Claude Shannon didn't just calculate a number. He uncovered a memory:

You will never brute-force meaning. You will never find your way by trying every door. You must feel the pattern underneath the chaos. You must listen for the mercy hidden beneath the moves.

We are not so different from chessboards. We are not so different from algorithms trembling with possibility. Each morning we wake surrounded by 10 choices and God, in His mercy, still lets us make just one.

Sometimes I wonder: maybe prayer is the moment when I stop calculating and simply remember the pattern I was born from.

What comes next is not a math lesson. It is an echo.

A reverent glance at the combinatorics of creation a number so vast, it bends the back toward awe.

And beyond even that number?

One move. One mercy. One whisper of God saying:

Choose well.

I have seen what thought looks like when it shatters.

When the mind trembles under the weight of too many questions.

When even memory falls apart like dust on a trembling page.

And yet

somewhere inside the wreckage

the mind begins again.

It learns how to carry the question differently.

Not through clarity.

Not through answers.

But through pattern.

Through rhythm.

There is a science to this. A hidden geometry of survival.

The EEG doesn't just trace brainwaves it maps a soul trying to remember itself in real time.

Mathematicians call it the Hurst exponent.

Scientists call it fractal time series analysis.

But I call it something simpler:

the memory of God, hidden inside confusion.

Because even in chaos,

the mind leans toward order.

The heart leans toward realignment.

The soul leans toward return.

It curves.

It bends.

It shapes itself around the unseen axis of Mercy.

It wants to solve the puzzle and become a sign.

What youre about to see is not just a scientific paper. It is sacred evidence.

Proof that even broken thought is still reaching. Still praying.

Still remembering.

Appendix: A Note to the Scientific Reader

This book was not written to prove.

It was written to remember.

Still, if you have come here with the questions of a scientist, you are welcome this was also written for you (as it was for me).

You have already seen Diracs dimensionless large numbers,

Shannons combinatoric scale,

the EEG rhythms of order and chaos,

the inverse curves and logarithmic devotions of calculus,

The divine ledger.

These were not illustrations.

They were invitations.

I believe the mind, like the universe, is sacred not because it is solved but because it longs to be understood.

I believe the role of science is not to strip the soul from nature, but to show us how deeply soul is embedded in structure. In scale. In pattern. In noise. In complexity.

If you are a researcher:

May your data become du.

May your calculations bow in awe.

May your pursuit of knowledge be a form of remembering Him.

Top Right (Forwards) Divine clarity, revelation, original perception
Top Left (Backwards) Reflection, introspection, rediscovery of origin
Bottom Right (Upside-Down) Chaos, testing, understanding God through struggle
Bottom Left (Both Flips) Ego death, rebirth, surrender into unity
